"This is Robert Menzies' debt crisis," you say firmly. "Labor warned against these terms in '47. We said the debt arrangement was unfair to Australian workers. Now the chickens are coming home to roost."

"Menzies negotiated this deal. Menzies put Australian exports at the mercy of American creditors. If American workers are now protesting those arrangements, perhaps the Prime Minister should have thought about that before he signed on the dotted line."

It's a deflection - you're not endorsing the strike, but you're not condemning it either. You're pointing the finger at Menzies.

Jim Healey frowns. "Eddie, that's weak. The wharfies took a stand. So should we."

But you've avoided taking a position that would explode the party.

**The party leadership will need to decide on an official position...**

